                <div class="article__teaser"><p>Interactions between a planet and its host star can produce observable effects on the star: tidal suppression of its dynamo effect, tidal inhibition of spin-down that can enhance activity, creation of hot spots or shrouding by a gaseous outflow from the planet, for example. Robert Parke Loyd and co-workers use the far ultraviolet (FUV) emission from GJ 436, an M dwarf with a close-in Neptune-size planet at 0.03 au, to look for signs of interactions with GJ 436 b.</p></div>
                
                
                    <div class="c-article-access-provider u-mb-32 u-mt-0">
                        <p class="c-article-access-provider__text u-sans-serif">This is a preview of subscription content, <a href="https://wayf.springernature.com?redirect_uri&#x3D;https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Farticles%2Fs41550-023-01933-x" data-track="click" data-track-action="institution access preview subscription" data-track-label="link">access via your institution</a></p>
                    </div>
                    
